When running the following program on a K64F, the timer value jumps drastically after 35 minutes.

``` C++
#include "mbed.h"
#include "rtos.h"

Timer tick;

int main()
{
    tick.start();

    for(;;)
    {
        printf("%lu\r\n", tick.read_ms());
        wait(1);
    }
}
```

Output after 35 minutes:

```
2144601
2145608
2146615
4292819952
4292820963
4292821973
```

Our current implementation of critical section uses `__disable_irq`, which looks fine for bare-metal.

The problem becomes when rtos is included. To illustrate:

```
// rtos present in this code
critical_section_enter();
printf("Hello\n");  // just for illustration, I could invoke here some RTOS code instead , the same result
critical_section_exit();
```

This fails for ARMCC as stdlib requires locking which is part of RTX (mutex for stdlib mutex_require/release calls). Therefore printf tries to acquire lock, but because interrupts are disabled (let's assume cortex-m0, leave BASEPRI out of the picture, we care about generic use case - any cortex). printf ends up in the hard fault. Because when mutex is called, it does `SVC 0x00`, this causes a hard fault.
h
We should consider RTOs version of critical section, it does not make sense there to disable interrupts anyway

